people before profit gives full support to striking teachers and lecturers. 





the union is entirely right to strike in response to the failure of the government to address pay inequality, which is creating real hardship for young teachers.





schools are facing real difficulties in recruiting teachers due to the low starting salaries. 





pbp is calling on parents and students to give full support to the teachers and lecturers who will be on strike.





all political parties who have been in power since 2010 are responsible for this discrimination against young teachers.





despite promises, the government has failed to address this discrimination and clearly, the tui has lost patience. 





we welcome the fact that the asti has agreed to ballot for similar action.  a sustained campaign of action can lead to the achievement of equal pay.





no trade union can tolerate a situation where two workers doing the same work are paid different rates of pay.





pbp tds proposed motions in the dail to end unequal pay but were blocked by the government using the so called â€œmoney messageâ€.





all parties must now declare that they will support the immediate abolition of the two tier pay system.





pbp say that the government must give a commitment that no sanctions will be taken against striking tui members arising from the public service pay and pension act.





this legislation represents an attack on trade union rights and the right to strike.  people before profit will make the repeal of such legislation a priority in the new dail.

text:
give soldiers a right to strike





the chief of staff of the defence forces vice-admiral mark mellet thinks that soldiers do not have a right to join the irish congress of trade unions


.


he claims that if pdfora, the soldiersâ€™ unions, are allowed to link up with the wider trade union movements, it would have â€˜potential security implications for the stateâ€™.





which only begs the question -what sort of state is frightened to give soldiers a basic freedom of association?





the irish state keeps soldiers in a state of subjugation so that it can get away with paying poverty wages.





the families of soldiers have had to come out of protest on their behalf. one of the spokespersons for the wives and partners of the defences forces put it like this:





â€˜our families live in poverty. we suffer from food, income, fuel, and child poverty. many of us can only dream of owning our home, and some this month are facing uncertainty about their homes, while others are facing homelessness. i personally know these peopleâ€™





in the last three years, 2,890 personnel of all ranks have left, representing an exodus of approximately 30% of the defence forcesâ€™ overall strength.





the soldiers want to join the ictu because this is where negotiations on their wages are conducted.





under irelandâ€™s bizarre form of social partnership, a few representatives from the ictu public sector committee join with government officials in negotiating rates of pay and even conditions for tens of thousands of public servants.





soldiers should have a right to be represented there.





but we go further â€“ they should also have a right to strike like every other worker.





soldiers in sweden have that right â€“ and, strangely, the state has not fallen apart.





soldiers in ireland should have full union rights, including the right to strike.

text:
to follow on from our policies on the arts which we posted earlier this week, we need to talk about public spaces for the arts, and what's required to create a vibrant artistic life in a city.





too many night-time venues and clubs have closed in the last few years, only to be bulldozed to make way for grey hotels or office blocks.





local councils must support more performances and exhibitions in public spaces - they should protect existing spaces from greedy developers too. 





to make matters worse, our archaic licensing laws strangle the life out of nightlife. clubs and other venues close earlier in dublin than they do anywhere else in europe. not only does this deny people the opportunity to access music and entertainment on their terms, it fuels other problems too - like anyone who has seen the city centre after 3am will attest to. it makes no sense to close all the clubs in the city at once.





we should follow the lead of the give us the night campaign, which calls for positive changes to our night-life.





for working people, the hours in the evening after work are when we are free to enjoy arts and culture but most venues are closed. galleries, theatres and other cultural spaces should offer late-night openings to better accommodate working people.





the arts and culture belong to the people - let's fund them properly and make them accessible to all!

text:
creche crisis â€“ caused by fine gaelâ€™s backing of insurance business





parents in many parts of the country are facing a crisis this xmas because they cannot find a place for their children in a creche.





the immediate cause is an attempt by the insurance industry to hike up charges. in some cases, they want to treble the cost of their premiums.





this is the latest twist in a scandal that is affecting irish society at many different levels.





in the past the insurance industry ripped off drivers and pushed up premiums to dramatically increase their profits. now they are trying the same trick with the countryâ€™s creches.





fine gael have repeated the lies of the insurance industry and have consistently justified their price hikes. they have, for example, blamed drivers for making fraudulent claims.





yet recent central bank report has revealed that the average motor insurance premium was up 42pc between 2009 and 2018, while the cost of claims fell by 2.5pc during in the same period. meanwhile, insurers made an average profit of 9pc last year.





people before profit have consistently exposed the  greed of the insurance industry. we proposed the formation of a state run insurance company, modelled on the one formed in manitoba in canada.





a not-for profit enterprise could provide far cheaper insurance, especially if linked to a less costly form of mediation to settle claims.





however irelandâ€™s system of childcare has deeper problems as well. it is the most expensive in europe because it relies almost exclusively on private enterprise. up to recently, there has been poor regulation and, in many instances creches, are underâ€”resourced.





people  before profit have proposed a national childcare service that would hire an extra 25,000 childcare professionals.





current services that are deemed best practice will be integrated into the new national service. the capitation grant should also be increased to make sure that parents only pay a maximum of 30% of the total cost of their childrenâ€™s care.





beyond that the state needs to move one based on a public system.

support delfin language teachers





language teachers at delfin english language school, in dublin have been on strike since september 23rd. they have held a series of stoppages lasting  half a day, one day and two days in support of their demands for union recognition, a pay increase, payment for all hours worked and proper holiday pay. this is an historic dispute as this is the first official dispute at a language school and the first school to have 100% union membership. the teachers are members of unite.





according to unite management  have totally failed to address the concerns of the workforce in relation to three main areas of contention: the need for pay to reflect the increased cost of living, the volume of unpaid work done by english language teachers on a daily basis, and the fact that teachers are left with no choice but to sign on for social welfare payments over the christmas period.





the management refuses to engage with the union and recognise unite.





part time lecturers in institutes of technology, some of whom are teaching languages, including english, get over â‚¬60 an hour. workers in delfin get less than a third of that.





this is an important dispute that must be won. workers in the industry and across the movement must get behind the delfin strikers. get motions passed in your union supporting them and contribute to their strike fund. send donations to unite the union. middle abbey street, dublin1, made out to the unite the union earmarking the donation for the delfin strikers.

text:
carlow college stands with student under threat of deportation:





the staff and students of carlow college, st patrickâ€™s are calling on the minister for justice, charlie flanagan to review the deportation case of a 1st year student, michael usiku. michael came to study in ireland five years ago but the two private colleges he attended in dublin both closed down before he could complete his degree.





michael applied for a place in carlow college on the social, political and community studies programme so he could qualify and return to his native malawi and work as a community worker.





however, his application for an extension to his student visa was denied, simply because the offer from carlow college didnâ€™t arrive in time. 





michael was served with a deportation order last week by the department of justice, stating that he must leave ireland by 29th december 2019. only the minister can revoke the deportation order and time is of the essence.





michael is not a burden on the state and has self-financed his education in ireland to date. the staff and students in carlow college are calling on minister flanagan to review michaelâ€™s case and lift the deportation order until he completes his degree. 





the campaign has garnered support locally and nationally, with the online petition gathering over 1000 signatures in just five days.





on monday 9th carlow county council passed an emergency motion to write to the minister for justice to ask for the deportation order to be reversed.





the union of students in ireland, which is the national representative body for third level students in ireland, is also calling on minister flanagan to revoke the deportation order.





further information about the campaign is available from stephanie hanlon, lecturer on the social, political and community studies programme in carlow college.





link to the petition: https://my.uplift.ie/petitions/keep-michael-in-ireland?fbclid=iwar17zcm0sra4f-toaz_mtlnzja0y-hs_vz8qkxckyrbmz9tgdsuj841ttku 





further information can be found on the college website: https://www.carlowcollege.ie/news/college-staff-and-students-are-calling-for-a-review-of-the-deportation-case-one-of-our-students/

text:
our housing proposals:





â€¢ hold a referendum to insert a â€˜right to housingâ€™ clause into the irish constitution: human rights do not just include political freedoms â€“ the state should have a legal obligation to provide housing.


â€¢ immediately declare a housing emergency: this will enable the state to borrow funds to begin a major house-building programme and to withdraw from paying out â‚¬500 million a year to private landlords.


â€¢ create a national construction company: there is no reason why the state cannot build houses. state-owned land is available and tens of thousands of construction workers either here or abroad who would be willing to work for decent wages.


â€¢ build 100,000 council houses over five years: this will cost â‚¬3 billion in the first year and a total of â‚¬14 billion over five years, but it will become self-financing by year six and into the future. this programme will also provide jobs in the construction sector and add to revenue receipts.


â€¢ control the price of building land to create affordable housing: you can build a three-bedroomed house for less than â‚¬200,000. if speculation in land were stopped, we could have cheaper housing.


â€¢ force nama to hand over land for public housing: this is public land â€“ it should be used to build council houses cheaply.


â€¢ stop the sell-off of public land to private developers: fine gael wants to sell off as much public land as cheaply as possible to their developer friends. this must be stopped. public land should be used for council and affordable housing and community amenities.


â€¢ implement rent controls and provide security of tenure: rents are too high. the poor are being forced out of their communities. we would freeze the rents immediately and create a system whereby tenants can seek a cut in rents. 


â€¢ create an independent review board for council tenants: at present, tenants cannot appeal decisions of their landlord â€“ the local authorities. 


â€¢ establish an independent national housing agency to oversee the delivery of safe and culturally appropriate traveller accommodation.


â€¢ ban economic evictions: vulture funds are trying to increase the rate of evictions because property prices have risen. landlords use loopholes such as renovations to evict tenants. if passed in the dÃ¡il, the solidarity-people before profit anti-eviction bill would have closed these loopholes and banned evictions in cases of demonstrable economic distress. we will continue to fight to stem the tide of evictions.


â€¢ impose a vacant dwelling levy: there are over 200,000 vacant properties in ireland â€“ even though thousands have no home. we need a â€˜use it or lose itâ€™ policy whereby private property owners will pay a special levy if their property is left empty for more than six months. we would impose a vacant land levy of 25 percent to be charged on land that is being held back for speculative reasons.


â€¢ use compulsory purchase orders: in some cases a levy will not be enough. if the public good demands it, the state should be able to use a cpo to attain appropriate accommodation.


â€¢ reverse the scandal of self-certification of building works: conduct immediate audits for fire and safety. create a redress fund for the 90,000 houses built during the celtic tiger era that have serious defects. levy the construction industry for this fund.





read our general election manifesto at www.pbp.ie

people before profit statement on monday's stormont sitting:





the deplorable attempt to re-establish stormont on monday is nothing more than a hypocritical stunt. 





not once did the dup call for stormont to be re-established to deal pip or universal credit which have been crippling communities across the north, or to deal with the crisis in our health or education systems.

user.name: People Before Profit
text:
childcare scandal





parents throughout the country are paying an average of â‚¬184 per week for full-time child care.





but the costs are far higher in dublin. in dÃºn laoghaire-rathdown parents of a child under one year could expect to be charged â‚¬265 per week for full-time care.





it shows that irelandâ€™s system of relying on private providers, a low paid workforce and state subsidies is not working.





the irish childcare system is badly underfunded and extremely expensive.





according to the oecdâ€™s education at a glance report 2017, irish expenditure on early yearâ€™s education amounts to only 0.1% of gdp (or 0.5% when over three year olds are included), significantly below the oecd average of 0.8%.





the highest levels of expenditure were recorded in the nordic countries which invest between 1.3% and 1.9% of gdp in early yearâ€™s education annually. 





this inevitably puts pressure on parents who use private operators to meet their childcare needs.





according to eurostat, however, 37.7% of parents identified financial concerns as a major impediment to accessing childcare facilities compared with just 0.7% in sweden and denmark.





meanwhile, a survey of 3,000 childcare workers found the average hourly wage is a little over â‚¬10 an hour. the net result is an expensive system that puts pressure on families and childcare professionals alike. 





our alternative is to move towards scandinavian levels of funding via a state run model of childcare. to do this, we would spend an extra billion split between newly hired state childcare workers and increased capacity in a national childcare system.





we would provide current childcare with a clear option to move into a state system and secure decent wages for those who work in this sector

text:
beef protests â€“ political establishment trying to break resistance





the full force of the political establishment is being deployed to break the beef protests.





rte has stepped up its propaganda; kepak meats has held back a â‚¬6 million investment and thousands of workers have been laid off.





behind this, stands the powerful hand of the meat processing industry. yet while attention has been focused on the farmers who are protesting, few are talking about the corporations who have cut the living standards of farmers and workers.





for every â‚¬10 spent on beef, the retailers get â‚¬5.10, the processors get â‚¬2.90 and the farmer gets just â‚¬2.00.





the average annual income for beef farmers in 2017 was just â‚¬12,529.





meat industry workers are treated no better.





in 2015, meat industry ireland made a submission to the low pay commission arguing against any increase in the minimum wage.





they often operate a system of roll over contracts where workers are employed by sub-contractors and let go regularly before they gain a legal entitlement to a permanent job.





meat industry ireland (mii) has said it doesnâ€™t know the profit margin of the thirteen irish meat processing companies it represents.





but companies like abp, owned by larry goodman, dawn, kepak are making fantastic profits as ireland becomes a major global exporter of beef.





last year, abp, for example, made â‚¬175 million in profits but goodman has routed much of his wealth through luxembourg to help avoid taxes.





these companies are at the root of the crisis in the irish beef sector. they are stepping up pressure on farmers by using laid off workers as their hostages.





we need to break their grip over irish society and its food production.





the meat processors should be taken into public ownership.





a fair basic price should be guaranteed to farmers.





with public support, there needs to be a just transition so that farmers who wish to exit beef production can be guaranteed a decent standard of living.

text:
our employment proposals:





whether you are a traditional manual worker or a white-collar worker, you need greater protection. yet low pay is on the rise, particularly for the young. many are in precarious, insecure employment. instead of a government that looks after corporations, we need one that ensures workers have more rights. people before profit support strong unions that stand up for workersâ€™ rights. today, many union leaders have become too close to employers and the government. they need to become more democratic and fight for their members. workers should also have a right to freedom of association â€“ to join a union of their choice. we will support the following legislative changes:





â¡ï¸ ban discrimination â€“ pay parity and restoration now: public sector workers hired after 2011 are paid less than those who joined before. additionally, some public sector workers are paid less than similarly qualified workers. nurses and teachers were right to strike for pay parity and restoration. we would repeal fempi terms and support public sector workers in their call for pay parity and restoration.





â¡ï¸ end the gender pay gap: it is completely unacceptable that women are paid less than men for doing the same work. this in-built sexism needs to be weeded out through legislation, union action and cultural changes.





â¡ï¸ give all workers equal rights from day one: whether you are part-time or full-time, temporary or permanent, you should have the same legal rights so that work conditions are not driven down.





â¡ï¸ guarantee unions the right to access all workplaces: unions should have the right to enter a workplace at least once a year to put the case for why people should join. they should also be able to inspect for adherence to labour legislation.





â¡ï¸ recognise unions for bargaining: when at least 20 percent of the workers join a union, they should have a right to collectively bargain with their employer through their chosen union.





â¡ï¸ ban zero-hour contracts: workers have a right to a guaranteed number of hours per week.





â¡ï¸ legislate for four extra holidays a year: with an annual right to 29 days holidays, workers in ireland have one of the lowest entitlements in europe. give workers a statutory right to bereavement leave.





â¡ï¸ raise the minimum wage to the living wage: a living wage is calculated on what one needs for a socially acceptable standard of living. it amounts to â‚¬12.30 an hour.





â¡ï¸ pay for internships: they are often used to exploit and dash the hopes of the young. they are also a free subsidy to businesses who get cheap labour.





â¡ï¸ bring labour agencies back into the public sector: end the practice of giving a bounty to private companies who force social welfare recipients to take up unsuitable jobs.





â¡ï¸ reform the insolvency act and companies act: workers should not be at the back of the queue. they should get the payments they are entitled to in redundancy situations.





â¡ï¸ introduce maximum 5:1 pay ratios in the public sector so that top managers do not earn more than five times those on junior grades. only award state contracts to private firms who adhere to this.





â¡ï¸ change industrial relations legislation: abolish the 1990 industrial relations act, which restrains workers from standing up for themselves. stop companies taking out injunctions against workers and give workers a right to express solidarity.





â¡ï¸ return the retirement age to 65: protect workersâ€™ pension rights.
